{"id":"2112.10320","submitter":"Zhengshuo Li","authors":"Yitong Liu, Zhengshuo Li, Junbo Zhao","title":"Robust Data-Driven Linear Power Flow Model with Probability Constrained\n  Worst-Case Errors","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"eess.SY cs.SY","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  To limit the probability of unacceptable worst-case linearization errors that\nmight yield risks for power system operations, this letter proposes a robust\ndata-driven linear power flow (RD-LPF) model. It is applicable to both\ntransmission and distribution systems and can achieve better robustness than\nthe recent data-driven models. The key idea is to probabilistically constrain\nthe worst-case errors through distributionally robust chance-constrained\nprogramming. It also allows guaranteeing the linearization accuracy for a\nchosen operating point. Comparison results with three recent LPF models\ndemonstrate that the worst-case error of the RD-LPF model is significantly\nreduced over 2- to 70-fold while reducing the average error. A compromise\nbetween computational efficiency and accuracy can be achieved through different\nambiguity sets and conversion methods.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 20 Dec 2021 03:23:59 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-12-21"}
