{"id":"2112.10385","submitter":"Yohsuke Imagi","authors":"Mohammed Abouzaid and Yohsuke Imagi","title":"Nearby Special Lagrangians","comments":"57 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.SG math.DG","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Let $X$ be a Calabi--Yau manifold and $Q\\subset X$ a closed connected\nembedded special Lagrangian. We use a combination of methods from Floer theory\nand from geometric analysis, to study those closed immersed special Lagrangians\n$L$ which are $C^0$-close to $Q$ and unobstructed in the sense of Floer theory.\nOur results are easiest to state under the assumption that the fundamental\ngroup $\\pi_1Q$ has no nonabelian free subgroup: we prove that every such nearby\nspecial Lagrangian $L$ as above is unbranched (that is, the projection $L\\to Q$\nis a covering map); moreover, if $\\pi_1Q$ is abelian then $L$ is a union of\nsmooth perturbations of $Q\\subset X.$ In comparison with Tsai--Wang's results,\ntheir Riemannian geometry assumptions on $Q\\subset X$ are replaced by the\npurely topological ones on $\\pi_1Q,$ at the cost of introducing the Floer\ntheory assumption on $L.$\n  The $\\pi_1Q$ conditions, the Floer theory condition and the special\nLagrangian condition are all essential to the statement above, as we show by\nconstructing counterexamples; they are branched $C^0$-nearby Lagranigans of\nMaslov class zero, which fail to satisfy the three kinds of conditions\nrespectively.\n  Our results have also applications to Morse--Novikov theory.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 20 Dec 2021 08:18:55 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-12-21"}
